com.infinitydb.map.visitor

Interface VisitableMap<K,V>

  • Type Parameters:
    K - the key of each Entry
    V - the value of each Entry
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    AirConcurrentMap, Visitable, VisitableArrayWrapper, VisitableListWrapper, VisitableMapWrapper, VisitableSetWrapper

    public interface VisitableMap<K,V>
    A Map that implements VisitableMap can be visited.

    It also provides a getVisitable(), which provides a Visitable, which allows configuration of a visitation in certain ways.

    A fast way to scan all of the key/value pairs of a VisitableMap or a Visitable is using visit(). Instead of two methods - hasNext() and next() - for an Iterator, there is only one method to invoke on each entry - MapVisitor.visit(Object, Object). There is also less logic than there is inside an iterator and less internal state. Also, each invocation of MapVisitor.visit() can avoid constructing a Map.Entry, as is done on each invocation of next() on the entrySet and in some Java 8 forEach() implementations, thereby reducing the GC load. The speed improvement can be great, partially because javac, JIT, the caches, and the cores can all benefit.

    A Visitable returned by getVisitable(), has several setup methods.

    For example, a Visitor for summing the values can be implemented this way: 

     static class Summer<K> extends MapVisitor<K, Long> {
     long sum;
 
     public void visit(K k, Long v) {
         sum += v.longValue();
     }
 
     long getSum(VisitableMap<K, Long> m) {
         // setting this zero makes an instance of Summer re-usable
         // Another choice is to make this usable with a regular Map somehow.
         sum = 0;
         m.visit(this);
         return sum;
     }
 }
 
 System.out.println("sum " + new Summer<Long>().getSum(m));
    The visitor instance can be re-used. Visitors are compatible with concurrent modifications of the VisitableMap if the Map is also a ConcurrentMap. Some visitors provide a method like the getSum() in the example to get the results given a regular Map as well, possibly using streams for example.

    For AirConcurrentMap, the performance improvement from using visitors over iterators can be two times (Iterators are already 2 to 3 times faster), over a wide range of Map sizes. The visitors also beat the Java 8 serial or parallel streams over the entire spectrum from 0 to full memory. The streams are very peaky and very slow outside the peak, while Visitors are good over the entire spectrum.

    There is also a ThreadedMapVisitor, subclass which makes it possible to use multiple internal threads to do the visitation, resulting in even more speed - about 3x over regular MapVisitors.

    In the current parallel implementation of AirConcurrentMap, any Exception stops the visitation.

    See Also:
    MapVisitor, ThreadedMapVisitor, RemoteMapVisitor, VisitableMapWrapper

    • Method Detail

      • getVisitable

        Visitable<K,V> getVisitable()
        Return the reference to the Visitable. The visitable can be configured in various ways. If no configuration is needed, just use visit(MapVisitor).
        Returns:
        A Visitable that can then be configured and visited normally. The configuration is like getVisitable().setXXX(..).visit(..)

      • visit

        void visit(MapVisitor<? super K,? super V> map)
        Visit the Map with visit(). This is like java 1.8 forEach() but faster when the map is an extension of ThreadedMapVisitor.
        Parameters:
        map - The map over which MapVisitor.visit(Object, Object) is invoked for each Entry.
